 <p><IMG SRC="http://user.tninet.se/~mhf993y/anna/sig2.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/unenabierdieb.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nena Bierdieb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/14/02 8:50:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=109>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I don't hate you Blizz</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  a guild is a guild and its like a family but to have 1officer or perhaps class officers decide who gets what will always lead to problems.. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It doesn't always lead to problems, it just doesn't work for every guild.  A pure award loot system requires trust on both ends, the awarding party trusting the recipient to view that item as a means to help the guild, and the guild members to trust that even if they didn't get the drop that time, it will likely come to them in time.<br>
<br>
It falls apart when the guild is so large that &quot;in time&quot; could conceivably mean a year rather than a few weeks or a month or two simply because there are so many people waiting for an item, especially for multi-class items.  Or it falls apart when too much of the guild is too new or too loot obssessed to honestly trust their guild.<br>
<br>
If you look at it by numbers, randoming won't get your guild outfitted any faster than awarding it.  If you have 10 warriors who want a ToV bp, no matter how you work it, someone has to be the 10th one.  Loot issues have a lot more to do with commitment than they do with how it's handed out.  The award system is just a good scapegood, no matter which one a guild uses. <p><img src=http://www.kaseyspace.com/EQ/nenasig.jpg align=center>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/upalimaxsceleris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Palimax Sceleris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Local Resident</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/14/02 9:08:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=110>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I don't hate you Blizz</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> actually i know of several Vision that where shopping for new guilds due to the palimax view of loot.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hurrah!  You've managed to point out what I already said.  What isn't true, however, is that we were EVER on the verge of collapse, which is what the unguilded guy keeps trying to say.<br>
<br>
Of course people shop guilds all the time.  Unless you're a GL or recruitment officer for a guild you have NO IDEA how many people are constantly shopping guilds.  Some of them are trying to find the right fit.  Some of them are trying to get more stuff for themselves.  What guild has the policies that give me the most stuff...  ....hrm....<br>
<br>
Any person who's ever done staffing would be proud of our turn-over rate, and many people who leave Vision ask to come back (and some of them even mature enough that we TAKE them back - heh).<br>
<br>
Also, you make a HUGE mistake in assuming they want to leave because of MY view of loot.  For starters, I don't make the policies at Vision.  I'm part of the process, but I'm only one of a handful of officers with that power.  Second, most items are given out by people other than me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> and its not very fair to say &quot;this ranger deserve it more because he has been to 3 more raids then you&quot; <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I disagree.  In some cases it's VERY fair to say exactly that.  <br>
<br>
Of course, the best part is, in Vision, we're pretty up-front about it.  You know what you're in for.  If you don't like the policies, it's not like we shoved 'em down your throat.  You OPTED to have them.  In fact, if it was your class' loot, you got to work with your CL to set that policy.  Every Ranger, for example, gets to talk to Cheeta and decide how their policy is going to work.  The rule is that they all have to agree that they like them -- or at least agree that they're fair and they can live with 'em.  So, if someone's complaining about the way *I* distribute loot, they need to understand either they disagree with our philosphy entirely, or that they simply didn't do a good job of working with their class and their officers to find a better solution*.<br>
<br>
....the best part is, that if anyone ever left Vision over loot, they're a liar; as they've always given another reason.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> [*For example, people suggest point systems for us all the time, then I ask them to track one that takes things like ports and the guy who made potions into account, and to keep tally for a month.  When they fail, I ask them what other suggestions they have.  :)  ]</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4868>Palimax Sceleris</a>,
